observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our recommendation that the Management:
• The Municipal Mayor direct the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Treasurer to include all types of properties in the physical count of PPE, submit the RPCPPE that includes all properties and the Report on Unserviceable Properties and coordinate closely with the Acting Municipal Accountant for the reconciliation of the RPCPPE with the accounting records;
• The Municipal Mayor assign additional staff to assist the Municipal Treasurer in the preparation of the PCs;
• The Acting Municipal Accountant maintain PPELCs for all PPE;
• The Municipal Treasurer prepare the RPCPPE in its prescribed form and accomplish all of the required information;
• The Municipal Treasurer create PCs per category of PPE indicating therein the relevant information for proper monitoring; and
• The Municipality undertake the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of government agencies as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended the following:
• The Municipal Mayor set up a stockroom where inventories will be delivered and stored prior to issuance to end-users;
• The Acting Municipal Accountant apply the perpetual inventory method in accounting for supplies and materials inventories;
• The Acting Municipal Accountant use the SSMI as basis for drawing the JEV to recognize the issuances of supplies and materials expenses;
• The Acting Municipal Accountant maintain SLCs for all types of inventories;
• The Municipal Treasurer consolidate the results of the physical count of inventories and submit it to the Acting Municipal Accountant to facilitate reconciliation of records;
• The Municipal Treasurer summarize the RIS, prepare the SSMI and submit to the Acting Municipal Accountant to serve as basis in accounting for the issuances of supplies and materials; and
• The Municipal Treasurer maintain SC for all types of inventories.

We recommended that:
• The Inventory Committee finish the conduct of physical count of PPEs and prepare a Report on Physical Count of PPE (RCPPE);
• The Municipal Mayor request inspection and valuation of the aforementioned properties to the COA Technical Audit Specialists (TAS);
• Based on the COA TAS recommendations, the agency undertake the disposal of properties; and
• The Municipal Accountant draw a JEV to drop the unserviceable properties from the books of accounts.

We recommended the following:

The Municipal Mayor direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of all PPE at least once a year, submit the RPCPPE that includes all properties and the Report on Unserviceable Properties and coordinate closely with the Acting Municipal Accountant for the reconciliation of the RPCPPE with the accounting records;

The Municipal Mayor assign additional personnel to the Municipal Treasurer to assist in the monitoring of PPE;

The Municipal Accountant maintain PPELCs for all PPE;

We recommended the following:

The Municipal Mayor set up a stockroom where inventories will be delivered and stored prior to issuance to end-users;

The Acting Municipal Accountant apply the perpetual inventory method in accounting for supplies and materials inventories;

The Acting Municipal Accountant use the SSMI as basis for drawing the JEV to recognize the issuances or the corresponding supplies and materials expenses;

The Acting Municipal Accountant maintain SLCs for all types of inventories;

The Municipal Treasurer consolidate the results of the physical count of inventories and submit it to the Acting Municipal Accountant to facilitate reconciliation of records;

The Municipal Treasurer summarize the RIS, prepare the SSMI and submit to the Acting Municipal Accountant to serve as basis in accounting for the issuances of supplies and materials; and

The Municipal Treasurer maintain SC for all types of inventories.

We recommended that Management:

Strictly comply with the requirements in the grant and liquidation of cash advances in accordance with existing rules and regulations;

Refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers and employees with existing unliquidated cash advance;



Require the immediate liquidation of cash advances upon completion of its purpose; and



Discontinue the practice of granting several cash advances nearing the last working day of the year.

We reiterated our recommendation and the Management agreed that:
The Municipal Mayor direct the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Treasurer to include all types of properties in the physical count of PPE, submit the RPCPPE that includes all properties and the Report on Unserviceable Properties and coordinate closely with the Acting Municipal Accountant for the reconciliation of the RPCPPE with the accounting records;
The Municipal Mayor assign additional staff to assist the Municipal Treasurer in the preparation of the PCs;
The Acting Municipal Accountant maintain PPELCs for all PPE;
The Municipal Treasurer prepare the RPCPPE in its prescribed form and accomplish all of the required information;
The Municipal Treasurer create PCs per category of PPE indicating therein the relevant information for proper monitoring; and
The Municipality undertake the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of government agencies as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Disbursing Officer discontinue the practice of requesting for cash advances despite lack of supporting documents such as approved payroll and/or list of payees indicating their net payments;
The Acting Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer refrain from approving cash advances that are not properly supported with complete documentation;
The Acting Municipal Accountant make sure that all cash advances and its liquidations are supported with complete documentation in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012; and
The MSWDO – Office Care Taker ensure that the details of the SAC are complete and the final beneficiaries are properly identified for future similar disbursements.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the Inventory Committee to:

Conduct annual inventory taking for Property, Plant and Equipment; 




Prepare a Report on Physical Count of Property Plant and Equipment with complete data; and

We recommended that:

The Inventory Committee finish the conduct of physical count of PPEs and prepare a Report on the Physical Count of PPE (RCPPE);



The Local Chief Executive create a Disposal Committee who will evaluate and appraise the value of the properties to be disposed;

The Municipal Mayor request inspection and valuation of the aforementioned properties to the COA Technical Audit Specialists (TAS);

Based on the COA TAS recommendations, the agency undertake the disposal of properties; and


The Municipal Accountant draw a JEV to drop the unserviceable properties from the books of accounts.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that:
The Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Assessor to prepare and submit a schedule bearing the names of landowners with areas and assessed value of the lands they own to the Municipal Treasurer to be used as basis for updating of Real Property Tax Account Register /Taxpayers’ Index Cards;
The Municipal Treasurer updates his Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayers’ Index Cards and submits a certified list of taxpayers with the corresponding amounts to the Municipal Accountant at the beginning of the calendar year. The total amount in the certified list should be reconciled with the total amount per schedule furnished by the Municipal Assessor;
The Municipal Accountant prepare a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to set up the receivable based on the duly certified list and ensure the proper recording of collection in the corresponding subsidiary ledger; and
The Municipal Accountant analyzes the causes of the discrepancies between reciprocal accounts and draws the necessary JEVs to adjust their balances.

We recommended that:
The Inventory Committee finish the conduct of physical count of PPEs and prepare a Report on the Physical Count of PPE (RCPPE);
The Local Chief Executive create a Disposal Committee who will evaluate and appraise the value of the properties to be disposed;
The Disposal Committee prepare an Inventory and Inspection Report on Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) and Waste Materials Report (WMR);
The Municipal Mayor request inspection and valuation of the aforementioned properties to the COA Technical Audit Specialists (TAS);
Based on the COA TAS recommendations, the agency undertake the disposal of properties; and
The Municipal Accountant draw a JEV to drop the unserviceable properties from the books of accounts.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) take the following courses of action:

Create an Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of PPEs valued at ₱49.331 million and require the preparation and submission of RPCPPE pursuant to Section 124, Volume 1 of  NGAS Manual for LGUs;

Instruct the General Services Office and the Municipal Accountant to maintain property ledger cards and subsidiary ledger for PPE respectively, and ensure that records are reconciled.  Also, require the Municipal Accountant to establish the book value of unserviceable properties and request for disposal of the same in accordance with Commission on Audit (COA) Memo No. 92-751. Upon approval of said request, prepare Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to drop from the books of accounts the unserviceable PPE.

We recommended the following:

The Local Finance Committee (LFC) ensure the integration of the GPB in the LGU budget proposals during the technical budget hearings;

The LFC ensure that GAD PPAs as indicated in the LGU GPB are reflected in the AIP;

GFPS regularly monitor if the GAD budget is being spent for what it was intended for and check on the actual cost of implementing the GAD activities; and

The GFPS and LFC look into the variance in amounts between the GPB, AIP and AR.

We recommended the following:

The LGU appropriate funds for the titling of the lots purchased;

The Municipal Assessor’s Office  take charge of the titling of all parcels of land of the Municipal Government;

The Municipal Accounting Office and the Treasurer’s Office maintain complete records of all real properties; and

The Municipal Accountant should review the basis of recording of the amount in the books of accounts and ensure that it was based on cost.

We recommended that:

The members of the Sangguniang Bayan and the Municipal officials revisit and assess the existing criteria/conditions in the availment of the MOBSP and amend the Municipal Ordinance;

The members of the Sangguniang Bayan should set a maximum amount (e.g. ₱5,000.00 per scholar) for the scholarship program with the identified number of slots (e.g. 20 slots) and disbursements shall be in consonance with the budget. Also, review the coverage of the MOBSP to provide for tuition fees only and payment of miscellaneous and other fees shall be the counterpart of the parents;   

Increase the average grade of high school graduates from the previous 78% and above to qualify as scholar.

Strictly implement the factor of indigency, among other factors in screening the applicants.

Require the scholars to render service in the municipality for a certain period of time such as summer jobs in the office or assist in the activities of the municipality to augment the existing limited workforce of the LGU.

